 the standard account of the Philhellenic movement and essential reading for any students of the Greek War of Independence, Byron, and European Romanticism. This completely revised edition includes a new introduction by Roderick Beaton, an updated bibliography and many new illustrations."--Publisher's website.10aByron, George Gordon Byron,cBaron,d1788-1824. 0aPhilhellenism. 0aGreecexHistoryyWar of Independence, 1821-1829xParticipation, Foreign.1 aBeaton, Roderick,ewriter of introduction.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher.40uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0001zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0001.jpgzConnect to cover image03602nam a2200529 i 99100947538970896620250313114120.0m        d        cr  n         121120t20112011enkb    sb    000 0 eng d  z9781906924546 (Hardback)  z9781906924539 (Paperback)  a9781906924553q(pdf)  a9781906924638q(epub)  a9781906924645q(mobi)  z2054-2437 (Print)  a2054-2445 (Online)  a(OCoLC)794698074  aStSaULbengelaterda0 aenghlat1 aCicero, Marcus Tullius,eauthor.10aIn Verrem.nActio 2.lEnglish10aCicero, Against Verres, 2.1.53-86h[electronic resource] :bLatin text with introduction, study questions, commentary and English translation /cIngo Gildenhard. 30aAgainst Verres, 2.1.53-86 1aCambridge :bOpen Book Publishers,c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (xiv, 191 pages) :b1 map.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier1 a[Classics textbooksx2054-2445 ;vvol. 1]  aAvailable through Open Book Publishers.  aOpen access resource providing free access.  aMode of access: World Wide Web.  aThis book is made available under the Creative Commons Attribution-Non-Commercial-No Derivative Works 2.0 UK: England & Wales License. For more detailed information consult the publisher's website.  aIncludes bibliographical references.0 aAcknowledgements -- Preface -- Introduction -- Latin text and study questions -- Commentary -- List of abbreviations -- List of rhetorical terms -- Translation -- Appendix: issues for further discussion -- Map.  a"Looting, despoiling temples, attempted rape and judicial murder: these are just some of the themes of this classic piece of writing by one of the world's greatest orators. This particular passage is from the second book of Cicero's Speeches against Verres, who was a former Roman magistrate on trial for serious misconduct. Cicero presents the lurid details of Verres' alleged crimes in exquisite and sophisticated prose. This volume provides a portion of the original text of Cicero's speech in Latin, a detailed commentary, study aids, and a translation. As a literary artefact, the speech gives us insight into how the supreme master of Latin eloquence developed what we would now call rhetorical "spin". As an historical document, it provides a window into the dark underbelly of Rome's imperial expansion and exploitation of the Near East. Ingo Gildenhard's illuminating commentary on this A-Level set text will be of particular interest to students of Latin at both high school and undergraduate level. It will also be a valuable resource to Latin teachers and to anyone interested in Cicero, language and rhetoric, and the legal culture of Ancient Rome."--Publisher's website.  aTranslated from the Latin.10aVerres, Gaius,d1st cent. B.C.10aCicero, Marcus Tullius. 0aSpeeches, addresses, etc., Latin. 1 aGildenhard, Ingo,d1970-eeditor,etranslator,ewriter of commentary.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher. 0aClassics textbooks ;vv 1.x2054-244540uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0016zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0016.jpgzConnect to cover image04909nam a2200529 i 99100947541970896620250313114121.0m        d        cr  n         121120t20122012enk     s     000 0 eng d  z9781906924461 (Hardback)  z9781906924454 (Paperback)  a9781906924478q(p