 societies develop and organise themselves, and in this book Agner argues that there is an evolutionary mechanism behind this flexible psychology. Incorporating a wide range of ideas including evolutionary theory, game theory, and ecological theory, Agner analyses the conditions that make us either strident or docile. He tests this theory on data from contemporary and ancient societies, and provides a detailed explanation of the applications of regality theory to issues of war and peace, the rise and fall of empires, the mass media, economic instability, ecological crisis, and much more. Warlike and Peaceful Societies: The Interaction of Genes and Culture draws on many different fields of both the social sciences and the natural sciences. It will be of interest to academics and students in these fields, including anthropology, political science, history, conflict and peace research, social psychology, and more, as well as the natural sciences, including human biology, human evolution, and ecology."--Publisher's website. 0aNational securityxPsychological aspects. 0aLeadershipzSocial aspects. 0aLeadershipxPsychological aspects. 0aWarfarevCross-cultural studies. 0aEvolutionary psychology. 0aEthnic groupsxPolitical aspects.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher.40uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0128zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0117.jpgzConnect to cover image04431nam a2200529 i 99100366115970896620250313114126.0m        d        cr  n         220211t20222022enka    sb    001 0 eng d  z9781800642430 (hbk.)  z9781800642423 (pbk.)  a9781800642447q(pdf)  a9781800642454q(epub)  a9781800642461q(mobi)  a9781800642478q(XML)  a(OCoLC)1312758304  aStSaULbengerda1 aspaheng  as-ck---1 aBaker, Geoffrey,d1970-eauthor.10aRethinking social action through music.lSpanish10aReplanteando la acción social por la músicah[electronic resource] :bla búsqueda de la convivencia y de l