ries important resonances for the way Eliot's novels generate their meanings. In this lively and provoking study, he tracks down those allusions and quotations that have hitherto gone unidentified by scholars, examining their relationship to the text in which they sit to unfurl a broader argument about the novel - both this novel, and the novel form itself. Middlemarch: Epigraphs and Mirrors is both a study of George Eliot and a meditation on the textuality of fiction. It is essential reading for specialists and students of George Eliot, the nineteenth century novel, and intertextuality. It will also richly reward anyone who has ever taken pleasure in Middlemarch."--Publisher's website. 10aEliot, George,d1819-1880.tMiddlemarchxCriticism and interpretation.  0aEpigraphs (Literature) 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher.40uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0249zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0249.jpgzConnect to cover image05445nam a2200493 i 99100169735970896620250313114119.0m        d        cr  n         210416t20212021enkh    sb    101 0 eng d  z9781800641655 (hbk.)  z9781800641648 (pbk.)  a9781800641662q(pdf)  z2632-6906 (Print)    z2632-6914 (Online)  a(OCoLC)1247662730  aStSaULbengerda00aNew perspectives in Biblical and Rabbinic Hebrewh[electronic resource] /cedited by Aaron D. Hornkohl and Geoffrey Khan. 1aCambridge :bOpen Book Publishers,c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (806 pages) :b2 colour facsimiles.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier1 aCambridge Semitic languages and culturesx2632-6914 ;v[volume 7]  aAvailable through Open Book Publishers.  aOpen access resource providing free access.  aMode of access: World Wide Web.  aThis work is licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International license (CC BY 4.0). For more detailed informa