om philosophy, neuroscience, and literary theory, Matthews posits the potential for science fiction to bridge the gap in understanding between AI and human minds. Given the recent advancements in AI technology, Matthews' timely discussion enters the speculative realm of sentient technology and postcyborg ethics. The work constitutes a major contribution to cross-disciplinary perspectives on alien and posthuman psychology, that engages with future states of existence in both ourselves and the machines we create. Transparent Minds will be of interest to innovators, authors, and science fiction enthusiasts alike."--Publisher's website. 0aScience fictionxHistory and criticism. 0aArtificial intelligence in literature. 0aConsciousness in literature.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher.40uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0348zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0348.jpgzConnect to cover image05260nam a2200505 i 99101420999970896620250313114123.0m     o  d        cr  n         231027t20232023enk     sb    001 0 eng d  z9781805111351 (hbk.)  z9781805111344 (pbk.)  a9781805111368q(pdf)  a9781805111405q(HTML)  a9781805111399q(XML)  a9781805111375q(epub)  a(OCoLC)1406070085  aStSaULbengerda1 aKoerber, Amyq(Amy Lunn),eauthor.14aThe predatory paradoxh[electronic resource] :bethics, politics, and practices in contemporary scholarly publishing /cAmy Koerber, Jesse C. Starkey, Karin Ardon-Dryer, R. Glenn Cummins, Lyombe Eko, and Kerk F. Kee. 1aCambridge :bOpen Book Publishers,c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (vi, 276 pages) :billustrations.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aAvailable through Open Book Publishers.  aOpen access resource providing free access.  aMode of access: World Wide Web.  aThis work is licensed under a CC BY-NC 4.0 Deed Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International license. For more detailed information consult the publisher's website.  aAdditional resources available from the publisher's website.  aIncludes bibliography (pages 261-264) and index.0 aIntroduction / Karin Ardon-Dryer, R. Glenn Cummins, Lyombe Eko, Kerk F. Kee, Amy Koerber, Jesse C. Starkey -- 1. Ethical, Legal, and Policy Issues in the Knowledge Creation Paradigm: The Case of OMICS International, Open Access, and 'Predatory' Publishing / Karin Ardon-Dryer, R. Glenn Cummins, Lyombe Eko, Kerk F. Kee, Amy Koerber, Jesse C. Starkey -- 2. Open Science, Open Data: The 'Open' Movement in Scholarly Publishing / Karin Ardon-Dryer, R. Glenn Cummins, Lyombe Eko, Kerk F. Kee, Amy Koerber, Jesse C. Starkey -- 3. Research Quality: Understanding Definitions of and Challenges to Quality in the Knowledge Production Process / Karin Ardon-Dryer, R. Glenn Cummins, Lyombe Eko, Kerk F. Kee, Amy Koerber, Jesse C. Starkey -- 4. Scientific Hoaxes and the Predatory Paradox: Past, Present, and Future / Karin Ardon-Dryer, R. Glenn Cummins, Lyombe Eko, Kerk F. Kee, Amy Koerber, Jesse C. Starkey -- 5. Avoiding the Pitfalls of Predatory Publishing: Guidance for Graduate Students and Junior Scholars / Lyombe Eko, Jesse C. Starkey, Amy Koerber, R. Glenn Cummins, Karin Ardon-Dryer, Kerk F. Kee -- 6. What's Being Taught about Predatory Publishing? A Systematic Review of University Resources / Kerk F. Kee, R. Glenn Cummins, Amy Koerber, Jesse C. Starkey, Lyombe Eko, Karin Ardon-Dryer -- 7. Predatory Paradoxes: What Comes Next? / Kerk F. Kee, Amy Koerber, Jesse C. Starkey, Karin Ardon-Dryer, R. Glenn Cummins, Lyombe Eko.  a"In today's 'publish or perish' academic setting, the institutional prizing of quantity over quality has given rise to and perpetuated the dilemma of predatory publishing. Upon a close examination, however, the definition of 'predatory' itself becomes slippery, evading neat boxes or lists which might seek to easily define and guard against it. This volume serves to foreground a nuanced representation of this multifaceted issue. In such a rapidly evolving landscape, this book becomes a field guide to its historical, political, and economic aspects, presenting thoughtful interviews, legal analysis and original research. Case studies from both European-American and non-European-American stakeholders emphasize the worldwide nature of the challenge faced by researchers of all levels. This coauthored book is structured into both textual and supplemental materials. Key takeaways, discussion questions, and complete classroom activities accompanying each chapter provide opportunities for engagement and real-world applications of these concepts. Crucially relevant to early career researchers and the senior faculty, library scholars, and administrators who mentor and support them, 'The Predatory Paradox: Ethics, Politics, and Practices in Contemporary Scholarly Publishing' offers practical recommendations for navigating the complex and often contradictory advice currently available. University instructors and teaching faculty will also find the reading essential in order to properly prepare both graduate and undergraduate students for the potential pitfalls endemic to scholarly publishing."--Publisher's website. 0aScholarly publishingxCorrupt practices. 0aPublishers and publishingxCorrupt practices. 0aCommunication in learning and scholarshipxMoral and ethical aspects. 1 aStarkey, Jesse C.,eauthor.1 aArdon-Dryer, Karin,eauthor.1 aCummins, R. Glenn,eauthor.1 aEko, Lyombe,eauthor.1 aKee, Kerk F.,eauthor.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher.40uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0364zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0364.jpgzConnect to cover image06483nam a2200433 i 99101421173970896620250313114124.0m     o  d        cr  n         231030t20232023enkad   sb    001 0 eng d  z9781805111283 (hbk.)  z9781805111276 (pbk.)  a9781805111290q(pdf)  a9781805111337q(HTML)  a9781805111320q(XML)  a9781805111306