he following societal conventions:  A power relation according to which stronger agents are able to force weaker ones to do things against their will ; A norm that categorizes actions as permissible or forbidden ; A status relation over alternatives which limits each agent's choices ; Systematic biases in agents' preferences. These four conventions are analysed using simple and mathematically straightforward models, without any pretensions regarding direct applied usefulness. While we do not advocate for the adoption of any of these conventions specifically - we do advocate that when modelling an economic situation, alternative equilibrium notions should be considered, rather than automatically reaching for the familiar approaches of prices or games."--Publisher's website. 0aEconomics models. 0aGame theory. 0aPricesxEconometric models.1 aRubinstein, Ariel,eauthor.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher.40uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0404zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0404.jpgzConnect to cover image04844nam a2200457 i 99101522929970896620250313114125.0m     o  d        cr  n         240426t20242024enkad   sb    001 0 eng d  z9781800648159 (hbk.)  z9781800648142 (pbk.)  a9781800648166q(pdf)  a9781800648203q(HTML)  a9781800648173q(epub)  a(OCoLC)1432460782  aStSaULbengerda  aev-----04aThe Nordic minueth[electronic resource] :broyal fashion and peasant tradition /cedited by Petri Hoppu, Egil Bakka, and Anne Fiskvik. 1aCambridge :bOpen Book Publishers,c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (viii, 578 pages) :b221 colour illustrations, 20 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aAvailable through Open Book Publishers.  aOpen access resource providing free access.  aMode of access: World Wide Web.  aThis work is licensed under an Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International (CC BY-NC 4.0) license. For more detail