II.3 Zionism, Then and Now / Susan Landau ; II.4 Nonviolent Activism / Susan Landau ; II.5 As a Jew / Susan Landau ; II.6 Antisemitism and Interfaith Relations / Susan Landau -- III. ENGAGING JEWISH VOICES OF CONSCIENCE AND DISSENT, POST 7 OCTOBER 2023 / Susan Landau. III.1 Initial Responses: In the Aftermath of 7 October 2023 / Susan LandauI ; II.2 Considering the Context: Settler Colonialism, Supremacy, and Hubris / Susan Landau ; III.3 Unbending the Arc: Genocide, Complicity, and Responsibility / Susan Landau ;III.4 Critical Distinctions: Antisemitism, Zionism,and Judaism / Susan Landau ; III.5 Praying With Our Feet: Jewish Values in Action / Susan Landau ; III.6 A Moral Reckoning: Statements of Conscience / Susan Landau ; III.7 The College Campus: Dissent, Repression, and Resistance / Susan Landau ; III.8 Affirming the Prophetic: Hope in Action / Susan Landau.  a"This volume is a timely and powerful collection of Jewish dissent against Zionism and the impact of Israeli statehood on the indigenous Palestinian population. Bridging history, politics, theology, and conflict studies, this book traces a moral and intellectual tradition of resistance from within the global Jewish community-one rooted in values of justice, equality, and compassion. From early twentieth-century critics like Ahad Ha'am and Hannah Arendt to contemporary scholars, rabbis, journalists, and activists, the voices gathered here challenge the dominant narratives that conflate Judaism with Zionism. As violence escalates in Gaza and misinformation clouds public understanding, this book offers essential historical context and urgently needed counter-narratives. Through curated quotes, essays, and reflections, it documents how generations of Jews have spoken out-often at personal cost-against militarism, racism, and settler colonialism. In doing so, it reclaims an ethical tradition that links solidarity with Palestine with all struggles for justice throughout the world. This is an anti-war, anti-prejudice book for anyone seeking clarity amid polarization. In this unprecedented political moment, it is an essential resource for educators, activists, faith leaders, and all who value human rights. By amplifying voices of conscience, it deepens our understanding of Israel-Palestine relations and reminds us of the enduring power of moral dissent."--Publisher's website. 0aAnti-Zionism. 0aSettler colonialismzPalestine. 0aHuman rightszPalestinexPublic opinion. 0aLand settlementxMoral and ethical aspectszPalestine. 0aJewsxPolitical activityzPalestine. 0aPalestinexForeign relationszIsrael. 0aIsraelxForeign relationszPalestine.1 aLandau, Susan,eeditor.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher.40uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0481zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0481.jpgzConnect to cover image04420nam a2200457 i 99101739126070896620251007154839.0m     o  d        cr||n|||||||||250801t20252025enk     sb    000 d eng d  z9781805116493 (hbk.)  z9781805116486 (pbk.)  a9781805116509q(pdf)  a9781805116523q(HTML)  a9781805116516q(epub)  a(OCoLC)1530081565  aStSaULbengerda  an-us---1 aEswaran, Mukesh,eauthor.14aThe economics of cultural lossh[electronic resource] :bharm and resilience in North American indigenous communities /cMukesh Eswaran. 1aCambridge :bOpen Book Publishers,c[2025] 4c©2025  a1 online resource (viii, 210 pages)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aAvailable through Open Book Publishers.  aOpen access resource providing free access.  aMode of access: World Wide Web.  aThis work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International (CC BY 4.0) license. For more detailed information consult the publisher's website and the back of the title-page.  aEPUB Accessibility Report available on publisher's website.  aIncludes bibliographical references (pages 169-198) and index.0 aForeword / Ronald L. Trosper -- Preface / Mukesh Eswaran -- Introduction: Culture and Indigenous Wellbeing / Mukesh Eswaran -- 2. A Simple Economic Model of an Indigenous Community / Mukesh Eswaran -- 3. Incorporating Cultural Belongingness / Mukesh Eswaran -- 4. The Failure of the Dawes' Act in America and Canadian Attempts to Privatize Indigenous Reserves / Mukesh Eswaran -- 5. Indigenous Historical Trauma in the North American Context / Mukesh Eswaran -- 6. An Economic Model to Capture Effects of Historical Trauma / Mukesh Eswaran -- 7. Some Adverse Effects of Historical Trauma on Indigenous Communities / Mukesh Eswaran -- 8. The Consequences for Indigenous Deaths of Despair / Mukesh Eswaran -- 9. Indigenous Survivance / Mukesh Eswaran -- 10. Some Concluding Thoughts / Mukesh Eswaran -- References / Mukesh Eswaran.  a"Why do North American Indigenous Peoples face such grave conditions in health, poverty, and mortality-including alarmingly high rates of suicide, alcoholism, and drug abuse? In this groundbreaking book, Mukesh Eswaran confronts these urgent questions through the lens of economics, focusing deeply on an underexplored aspect: the erosion of Indigenous culture. While empirical studies have shed some light on Indigenous struggles, Eswaran argues that mainstream economic theory fails to grasp the unique realities of Indigenous communities. His work introduces innovative models that incorporate cultural and communal values-particularly the sacredness of land and the importance of extended family and communal life-as foundational components of Indigenous well-being. Eswaran emphasizes that policies rooted in conventional economics, which often ignore culture, are ill-suited to address Indigenous issues, in particular, what has been identified as 'Deaths of Despair' among Indigenous Peoples. Drawing from Indigenous scholars and Elders, he shows how historical trauma-passed through generations-has systematically dismantled cultural and communal supports. His theoretical framework helps explain the rise in substance abuse and suicide, and points toward new, culturally sensitive policy approaches. While advancing economic theory relevant to Indigenous issues, the book also proposes a meaningful path toward healing and justice for Indigenous communities. It is a vital read for economists, policymakers, students, and anyone concerned with Indigenous history, well-being, equity and reconciliation."--Publisher's website. 0aIndians of North AmericaxSocial conditions. 0aIndians of North AmericaxEconomic conditions. 0aIndians of North AmericaxMental health. 0aCultural propertyxProtectionzUnited States.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher.40uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0477zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0477.jpgzConnect to cover image09246nam a2200553 i 99101739126270896620251007154638.0m     o  d        cr||n|||||||||250724t20252025enk     sb    001 0 eng d  z9781805110712 (hbk.)  z9781805110705 (pbk.)  a9781805110729q(pdf)  z2632-6906 (Print)  z2632-6914 (Online)  a(OCoLC)1528868114  aStSaULbengerda0 aengaheb  af-ua---11aArad, Dotan,eauthor.00a'Wisdom and greatness in one place' :bthe Alexandrian trader Moses ben Judah and his circleh[electronic resource] /cDotan Arad and Esther-Miriam Wagner. 1aCambridge :bOpen Book Publishers,c[2025] 4c©2025  a1 online resource (x, 538 pages)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier1 aCambridge Semitic languages and culturesx2632-6914 ;vvol. 37  aAvailable through Open Book Publishers.  aOpen access resource providing free access.  aMode of access: World Wide Web.  aThis work is licensed under an Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International (CC BY-NC 4.0) license. For more detailed information consult the publisher's website.  aAt head of front cover: Cambridge Semitic languages and cultures.  aAt foot of cover: Uni