s and Territories' offers a comprehensive exploration of the challenges and strategies involved in managing dengue vectors, particularly Aedes mosquitoes, in the US and its territories. With over 13 million dengue cases reported in the Americas in 2024 alone, this timely book synthesizes critical information on vector species, transmission cycles, and effective surveillance and control methods.Dr. Roberto Barrera, a seasoned expert in mosquito ecology and Vector-Borne diseases, presents evidence-based recommendations for public health officials, researchers, and community stakeholders. This essential guide not only addresses the complexities of dengue transmission but also emphasizes the importance of integrated vector management and community engagement in preventing outbreaks. Whether you are a public health professional, a student, or simply interested in vector ecology, this book serves as a vital resource for understanding and combating dengue in an ever-evolving landscape."--Publisher's website. 0aDenguexTransmissionzUnited States. 0aDenguezUnited StatesxProtection. 0aDenguexRisk factorszUnited States.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher.40uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0472zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0472.jpgzConnect to cover image04089nam a2200505 i 99101741276870896620250815151811.0m#####o##d########cr||n|||||||||250812t20252025enka    sb    000 d eng d  z9781805116332 (hbk.)  z9781805116325 (pbk.)  a9781805116349q(pdf)  a97818051163631q(HTML)  a9781805116356q(epub)  a(OCoLC)1531060947  aStSaULbengerda  ae-it---1 aShephard, Tim,eauthor.10aSounding the bookshelf 1501h[electronic resource] :bmusic in a year of Italian printed books.nVolume 1 /cTim Shephard, Oliver Doyle, Ciara O'Flaherty, Annabelle Page, and Laura Ştefănescu. 1aCambridge :bOpen Book Publishers,c[2025] 4c©2025  a1 online resource (vi, 380 pages) :b4 illustrations.  atextbtxt2rd