usical discourse. Set against the backdrop of 1501-a landmark year when Ottaviano Petrucci revolutionized music printing-this book offers a compelling snapshot of how music was understood and discussed by ordinary readers in Renaissance Italy. By sounding out these diverse voices, the project reimagines the contours of music history and opens new avenues for musicological inquiry."--Publisher's website. 0aMusiczItalyxHistoryy15th century. 0aMusiczItalyxHistoryy16th century. 0aMusicxSocial aspectszItalyxHistory and criticism. 0aHearingxSocial aspectszItalyxHistory and criticism.1 aOliver Doyle,eauthor.1 aO'Flaherty, Ciara,eauthor.1 aPage, Annabelle,eauthor.1 aŞtefănescu. Laura,eauthor.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher.40uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0473zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0473.jpgzConnect to cover image04475nam a2200481 i 99101741276890896620250812143159.0m#####o##d########cr||n|||||||||250812t20252025enkad   sb    000 d eng d  z9781800642492 (hbk.)  z9781800642485 (pbk.)  a9781800642508q(pdf)  a9781800646681q(HTML)  a9781800642515q(epub)  a(OCoLC)1529965673  aStSaULbengerda1 aenghger1 aEder, Jens,eauthor.10aCharacters in film and other mediah[electronic resource] :btheory, analysis, interpretation /cJens Eder ; translated by Stephen Lowry in collaboration with Jens Eder. 1aCambridge :bOpen Book Publishers,c[2025] 4c©2025  a1 online resource (vi, 380 pages) :b96 illustrations, 13 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aAvailable through Open Book Publishers.  aOpen access resource providing free access.  aMode of access: World Wide Web.  aThis work is licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International (CC BY-NC 4.0) license. For more detailed information consult the publisher's website and the back of the title-page.  a"This book is the translated and revised edition of Die Figur im Film : Grundlagen der Figuranalysen (Marburg : Schüren, 2008 ; 2nd edition, 2014"--Back of title-page.  aEPUB Accessibility Report available on publisher's website.  aIncludes bibliography (pages 755-802), filmography (pages 803-815) and indexes.0 aIntroduction / Jens Eder -- 2. Research on Characters: An Overview (T) / Jens Eder -- 3. What Are Characters, How Are They Created and Experienced? (T) / Jens Eder -- 4. A Basic Model for Analysis: The Character Clock / Jens Eder -- 5. Grasping Represented Beings: Forming Mental Models of Characters (T) / Jens Eder -- 6. Analysing Represented Beings: An Anthropological Heuristic / Jens Eder -- 7. Shaping Characters with Cinematic Means: Sensuality and Structure / Jens Eder -- 8. Characters as Artefacts: Aesthetic Qualities and Conventions / Jens Eder -- 9. Motivation and Plot: Characters' Needs, Goals, and Actions / Jens Eder -- 10. Character Constellations as Social and Aesthetic Systems / Jens Eder -- 11. Characters as Symbols: How Characters Convey Higher-Level Meanings / Jens Eder -- 12. Characters as Symptoms: How Characters Interact with Reality / Jens Eder -- 13. Imaginative Involvement with Characters: A Matter of Perspective / Jens Eder -- 14. Affective Involvement with Characters: Sympathy, Empathy, and Beyond /    Jens Eder -- 15. Summary: Fundamentals of Character Theory and Analysis / Jens Eder -- 16. A Challenging Case: Characters and the Weight of Reality in Death and the Maiden / Jens Eder.  a"Characters are central to the creation and experience of films and other media. Their cultural significance is profound, but they also raise a wide range of questions. This book provides a comprehensive theory that guides the analysis and interpretation of characters across four dimensions: as represented beings with physical, psychological, and social characteristics; as artefacts with aesthetic structures; as meaningful symbols; and as symptoms of socio-cultural origins and effects. Integrating insights from film, media, and literary studies as well as philosophy, psychology and sociology, the book offers a broad range of approaches for understanding characters and the emotional responses they evoke. Richly illustrated and offering practical tools, along with case studies of numerous characters from different genres of films, this book will be invaluable to scholars and students of film and media studies and related disciplines, as well as artistic practitioners."--Publisher's website.  aTranslated from the German. 0aCharacters and characteristics in motion pictures. 0aAffect (Psychology) in motion pictures.1 aLowry, Stephen,etranslator.1 aEder, Jens.tFigur im Film.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher.40uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0283zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0283.jpgzConnect to cover image03959nam a2200457 i 99101741526920896620250829122933.0m#####o##d########cr||n|||||||||250815t20252025enka    sb    001 d eng d  z9781805115571 (hbk.)  z9781805115564 (pbk.)  a9781805115588q(pdf)  a9781805115601q(HTML)  a9781805115595q(epub)  a(OCoLC)1534046757  aStSaULbengerda  ae-uk-en1 aSaunders, Tom,eauthor.10aCity of capital and labourh[electronic resource] :bthe making and transformation of industrial Manchester /cTom Saunders. 1aCambridge :bOpen Book Publishers,c[2025] 4c©2025  a1 online resource (xxii, 312 pages) :b238 illustrations.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aAvailable through Open Book Publishers.  aOpen access resource providing free access.  aMode of access: World Wide Web.  aThis work is licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International (CC BY-NC 4.0) license. For more detailed information consult the publisher's website and the back of the title-page.  aEPUB Accessibility Report available on publisher's website.  aIncludes bibliographical references (pages 293-298) and index.0 aIntroduction / Tom Saunders -- 1. The Georgian Boom Town, c1720-c1780 / Tom Saunders -- 2. The 'Shock City' of Industrial Capitalism, c1780-c1840 / Tom Saunders -- 3. City of Triumphant Liberalism, c1840-c1860 / Tom Saunders -- 4. City of Civic Pride and Industrial Paternalism, c1860-c1890 / Tom Saunders -- 5. City of Ambition and Popular Culture, c1890-c1920 / Tom Saunders -- Conclusion / Tom Saunders.  a"This compelling book explores the evolution of industrial Manchester, offering a fresh perspective on its built environment through the lens of architecture, archaeology, and social history. Richly illustrated and designed for both academic and general audiences, it sheds new light on Manchester's transformation during the Industrial Revolution, highlighting how the city's physical form shaped and was shaped by its socio-economic and cultural dynamics. By analysing architectural styles, building types, land use, and spatial relationships, the study identifies distinct phases of development from the early eighteenth to early twentieth century. It delves into how Manchester's material landscape mediated industrialisation and social tensions, reflecting the emergence of both bourgeois and proletarian communities. The book argues that the city's evolving physical structure was deeply intertwined with the capitalist logic of class relations, where architecture and urban spaces became arenas for competing social identities. Through mapping the enduring physical traces of these changes, and using a Marxist lens to examine shifting power structures in cities, the book underscores Manchester's role as a microcosm of industrial and urban transformation. It invites readers to rediscover the city's industrial heritage, emphasising the importance of its historic buildings in understanding the socio-economic forces that shaped modern urban life-before they are irrevocably altered by contemporary redevelopment"--Publisher's website. 0aCity planningzEnglandzManchesterxHistoryy19th century.  aUrban policyzEnglandzManchesterxHistoryy19th century. 0aManchester (England)xBuildings, structures, etc. 0aManchester (England)xSocial conditions.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher.40uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0459zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0459.jpgzConnect to cover image04565nam a2200553 i 99101742346810896620250829105927.0m#####o##d########cr||n|||||||||240604t20252025enk     sb    001 0 eng d  z9781805116387 (hbk.)  z9781805116370 (pbk.)  a9781805116394q(pdf)  z2632-6906 (Print)  z2632-6914 (Online)  a(OCoLC)1534046954  aStSaULbengerda1 aengalatahebagrc1 aRodrigue, Paul,eauthor,etranslator.10aJerome's sources in his translation of the Hebrew Bibleh[electronic resource] :cPaul Rodrigue. 1aCambridge :bOpen Book Publishers,c[2025] 4c©2025  a1 online resource (xviii, 350 pages)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier1 aCambridge Semitic languages and culturesx2632-6914 ;vvol. 38  aAvailable through Open Book Publishers.  aOpen access resource providing free access.  aMode of access: World Wide Web.  aThis work is licensed under an Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International (CC BY-NC 4.0) license. For more detailed information consult the publisher's website.  aAt head of front cover: Cambridge Semitic languages and cultures.  aAt foot of cover: University of Cambridge, Faculty of Asian and Middle Eastern Studies.  aIncludes bibliography (pages 315-346) and indexes.  aChiefly English ; text examples in Latin, Hebrew, Greek and Aramaic.0 a1. Introduction / Paul Rodrigue -- 2. The Translation of the Joseph Story (Gen 37-50) / Paul Rodrigue -- 3. The Translation of the Book of Daniel / Paul Rodrigue -- 4. The Translation of the Book of Esther / Paul Rodrigue -- 5. Conclusion / Paul Rodrigue.  a"At the close of the fourth century CE, Jerome of Stridon-renowned Latin scholar, theologian, and priest-undertook the monumental task of translating the Hebrew-Aramaic Bible into Latin. The result of this effort, now known as the Vulgate, has long been regarded as a foundational text of Western Christianity. In this volume, Paul Rodrigue investigates the sources that Jerome may have drawn upon in the process of translation. Far from being just a rendering of the Hebrew-Aramaic Bible, the Vulgate emerges as a layered and multifaceted translation, shaped not only by the Hebrew-Aramaic text but also by a broad array of additional sources. Through a series of carefully chosen case studies, Rodrigue analyses a number of verses from the Joseph narrative in Genesis, as well as from Daniel and Esther. Each Vulgate passage is meticulously compared with its equivalents in the Hebrew-Aramaic Bible, the Septuagint, the Latin translations of the Septuagint, the Greek versions of Aquila, Symmachus, and Theodotion, and-where applicable-the Targumim and rabbinic writings. This comparative approach reveals Jerome's engagement with texts in four languages-Hebrew, Aramaic, Greek, and Latin-and highlights his responses to both Jewish and Christian exegetical traditions. Importantly, the selected translations span Jerome's career as a translator of the Hebrew-Aramaic Bible: Daniel at its outset (392-393), Genesis mid-career (late 390s), and Esther at its close (404-405). As such, Rodrigue's analysis offers a chronologically nuanced study of Jerome's evolving translation method (sensus de sensu), providing invaluable insight for scholars of biblical studies, late antiquity, translation theory, and the transmission of sacred texts."--Publisher's website.00aJerome,cSaint,d-419 or 420xCriticism and interpretation.00aJerome,cSaint,d-419 or 420xKnowledgexGreek philology.00aJerome,cSaint,d-419 or 420xKnowledgexHebrew philology.00aBiblexTranslatingxHistoryvSources.00aBible.pGenesisxCriticism, interpretation, etc.00aBible.pDanielxCriticism, interpretation, etc.00aBible.pEstherxCriticism, interpretation, etc.2 aUniversity of Cambridge.bFaculty of Asian and Middle Eastern Studies.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher. 0aSemitic languages and cultures ;vv. 38.x2632-691440uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0474zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0474.jpgzConnect to cover image03200nam a2200433 i 99101742366720896620251007154922.0m     o  d        cr||n|||||||||250829t20252025enk     sb    000 d eng d  z9781805116745 (hbk.)  z9781805116738  (pbk.)  a9781805116752q(pdf)  a(OCoLC)1535231180  aStSaULbengerda1 aenghlat1 aPlautus, Titus Maccius,eauthor.10aCasina by Plautush[electronic resource] :ban annotated Latin text with a prose translation /cby Catherine Tracy (based on the Latin text of W.M. Lindsay). 1aCambridge :bOpen Book Publishers,c[2025] 4c©2025  a1 online resource (viii, 229 pages)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aAvailable through Open Book Publishers.  aOpen access resource providing free access.  aMode of access: World Wide Web.  aThis work is licensed under a Creative Commons Attributionl 4.0 International No-Commercial No-Derivatives (CC BY-NC-ND 4.0) license. For more detailed information consult the publisher's website and the back of the title-page.  aIncludes bibliographical references (pages 222-226) and index.  aText of play in Latin with English translation ; introduction and further editorial material in English.0 aIntroduction / Catherine Tracy -- Helpful Information for Reading the Latin Text / Catherine Tracy -- Casina (Annotated Latin Text) /   Catherine Tracy -- Casina (in Translation) / Catherine Tracy.  a"'Casina' was written for audiences in ancient Rome, but tells the story of an Athenian man and his son competing for the affections of a young enslaved woman who was brought up in their household. Deception, disguise, and domestic conflict unfold as the old man's schemes are cleverly thwarted by his wife. Likely one of Plautus's later works, 'Casina' offers both linguistic challenge and comic brilliance, making it ideal for classroom use or independent study. This edition features the complete Latin text of the play, richly annotated with grammatical and vocabulary notes to support comprehension. A clear prose translation accompanies the original, offering accessible insight into the humor and intrigue of the play. The introduction provides historical and cultural context, situating the farce within ancient Athenian and Roman comedic traditions. This volume is designed for students with intermediate Latin skills who wish to engage directly with Plautus's lively comic play."--Publisher's website.10aPlautus, Titus Maccius.tCasina.10aPlautus, Titus MacciusxCriticism and interpretation. 0aLatin drama (Comedy)xHistory and criticism.1 aTracy, Catherine,eeditor,etranslator,eauthor.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher.40uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0482zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0482.jpgzConnect to cover image05219nam a2200469 i 99101744009450896620251007155101.0m     o  d        cr||n|||||||||250909t20252025enkad   sb    001 d eng d  z9781805116592 (hbk.)  z9781805116585 (pbk.)  a9781805116608q(pdf)  a9781805116622q(HTML)  a9781805116615q(epub)  a(OCoLC)1535815135  aStSaULbengerda00aInterprofessional approach to refugee healthh[electronic resource] :ba practical guide for interdisciplinary health and social care teams /cedited by Emer McGowan, Djenana Jalovcic and Sarah Quinn. 1aCambridge :bOpen Book Publishers,c[2025] 4c©2025  a1 online resource (xx, 386 pages) :b23 colour illustrations, 6 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aAvailable through Open Book Publishers.  aOpen access resource providing free access.  aMode of access: World Wide Web.  aThis work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International (CC BY 4.0) license. For more detailed information consult the publisher's website and the back of the title-page.  aEPUB Accessibility Report available on publisher's website.  aIncludes bibliographical references and index.0 aForeword -- Introduction / Emer McGowan, Djenana Jalovcic, Sarah Quinn -- 1. Global Migrations and Persons with Refugee Experiences / Huseyin Emlik -- 2. Refugee Rights Are Human Right / Sandra Schiller, Djenana Jalovcic -- 3. Providing Person-Centred Care, Creating Therapeutic Space and Recognizing the Needs of Service Users / Rolf Vardal, Emer McGowan, Sarah Quinn -- 4. Recognizing the Needs of Refugees: A Healthcare Access Lens / Ganzamungu Zihindula -- 5. Pathways to Healing: Expressive Arts Practice with Adolescent Refugees / Rachel Hoare -- 6. Promoting Interaction and Mutual Learning Between Local and Refugee Communities / Méabh Bonham Corcoran, Sarah Quinn, Frédérique Vallières -- 7. Evidence-Informed Practice and Learning Through Critical Reflection / Sarah QuinnEmer McGowan8. Engagement and Disengagement: Reflecting on the Challenges for Professionals in Supporting Those Seeking Refuge / Fintan Sheerin -- 9. Ethical Practice and Personal Conduct in Refugee Health / Sandra Schiller -- 10. Culturally Responsive Practice in Refugee Health / Sandra Schiller, Angelika Roschka, Kathrin Weiss -- 11. Cross-Cultural Communication in Refugee Health / Sandra Schiller, Andreas Wolfs -- 12. Advanced Clinical Reasoning / Kerstin Berr, Franziska Grünberg-Lemli, Kathrin Weiss -- 13. Advocacy and Empowerment in the Context of Refugee Health / Sandra Schiller -- 14. Flight and Post-Traumatic Stress: Their Influence on a Person's Identity / Christine Spevak-Grossi.  a"As global displacement reaches unprecedented levels, health and social care professionals increasingly find themselves supporting people with refugee experience whose health and wellbeing needs are complex, urgent, and often unmet. This timely and practical book provides essential guidance for professionals-particularly those new to working in this context-on how to deliver compassionate, culturally responsive, and effective care to forcibly displaced individuals and communities. Drawing on personal narratives of displacement, international research, global best practices, and firsthand professional experience, this volume addresses the many challenges refugees face in accessing appropriate health and social care, including trauma, chronic illness, mental health conditions, housing insecurity, and language barriers. Contributions from a diverse range of professionals-across nursing, occupational therapy, psychology, psychotherapy, physiotherapy, speech and language therapy, and more-highlight the interprofessional collaboration necessary to meet these multifaceted needs. Through real-life case studies, reflective prompts, and a strong focus on person-centred, equitable care, this book centres the lived experiences of refugees and emphasizes the importance of listening, learning, and adapting care to each individual's story. A vital resource for practitioners, students, policymakers, and educators, this book bridges the gap between evidence and practice and empowers professionals to build inclusive and responsive systems of care for those affected by forced migration."--Publisher's website.  aFunded by Western Norway University of Applied Sciences. 0aRefugeesxHealth and hygiene. 0aRefugeesxHealth and hygienevCase studies.1 aMcGowan, Emer,eeditor.1 aJalovcic, Djenana,eeditor.1 aQuinn, Sarah,eeditor.2 aWestern Norway University of Applied Sciences,efunding body.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher.40uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0479zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp