ing Samdrup -- 7. The Telephone ཁ་པར། / Menla Jyab, Timothy Thurston, Tsering Samdrup -- 8. Careful Village's Grassland Dispute སེེམས་ཆུང་སྡེེ་བའིི་ས་རྩོོད། / Menla Jyab, Timothy Thurston, Tsering Samdrup -- 9. Careful Village's Bride སེེམས་ཆུང་སྡེེ་བའིི་མནའ་མ། / Menla Jyab, Tsering Samdrup, Timothy Thurston -- 10. Careful Village's Wedding སེེམས་ཆུང་སྡེེ་བའིི་སྟོོན་མོོ། / Menla Jyab, Timothy Thurston, Tsering Samdrup -- 11. Careful Village's Thief སེེམས་ཆུང་སྡེེ་བའིི་རྐུན་མ། / Menla Jyab, Timothy Thurston, Tsering Samdrup.  a"This volume offers a unique glimpse into the world of khashag, a vibrant genre of Tibetan spoken comic dialogues from the area Tibetans call Amdo, with the first ever publication of 11 annotated translations of scripts by its leading performer, Menla Jyab. Emerging in the 1980s during a period of cultural revival in Tibetan communities, khashag fused traditional Tibetan expression with influences from Han Chinese xiangsheng (crosstalk), evolving into a medium of sharp societal critique and joyous entertainment. Menla Jyab, a pioneering performer, used his platform in radio, television, to craft comedies described as 'having meaning in every line'. Drawing on a decade and a half of Tim Thurston's research and his and Tsering Samdrup's close connections with Menla Jyab, this groundbreaking work brings these culturally significant performances to English-speaking audiences for the first time. This richly contextualized volume explores the genre's linguistic intricacies, performative brilliance, and cultural resonance, highlighting its role in overcoming literacy barriers to reach a broad audience. The translations, based on published scripts and transcribed recordings, are accompanied by insightful notes that illuminate the subtle interplay of humor, critique, and identity in Tibetan life. Careful Village is an indispensable resource for scholars and enthusiasts of Tibetan culture, performance studies, and oral traditions."--Publisher's website.10aJyab, MenlaxCriticism and interpretation.. 0aFolk drama, TibetanvTexts. 0aFolk drama, TibetanzChinazAmdo (Region)vTexts. 0aFolk drama, TibetanxHistory and criticism. 0aTibetan drama (Comedy)vTranslations into English. 0aTibetan drama (Comedy)xHistory and criticism.1 aThurston, Timothy,etranslator,ewriter of introduction.1 aSamdrup, Tsering,etranslator,ewriter of introduction.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher. 0aWorld oral literature series ;vv. 13.x2054-362X40uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0452zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0452.jpgzConnect to cover image04106nam a2200397 i 99101745077930896620251007155228.0m     o  d        cr||n|||||||||250916t20252025enk d   sb    001 d eng d  z9781805117070 (hbk.)  z9781805117063  (pbk.)  a9781805117087q(pdf)  a(OCoLC)1537554285  aStSaULbengerda1 aOsborne, Martin J.,eauthor.10aModels in political economyh[electronic resource] :bcollective choice, voting, elections, bargaining, and rebellion /cMartin J. Osborne. 1aCambridge :bOpen Book Publishers,c[2025] 4c©2025  a1 online resource (xvii, 552 pages)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aAvailable through Open Book Publishers.  aOpen access resource providing free access.  aMode of access: World Wide Web.  aThis work is licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives 4.0 International (CC BY 4.0) license. For more detailed information consult the publisher's website and the back of the title-page.  aIncludes bibliographical references (pages 513-526) and index.0 a1. Collective choice with known preferences / Martin J. Osborne -- 2. Collective choice with privately-known preferences / Martin J. Osborne -- 3. Voting with two alternatives / Martin J. Osborne -- 4. Voting with many alternatives: plurality rule / Martin J. Osborne -- 5. Sequential pairwise voting / Martin J. Osborne -- 6. Ethical voting and expressive voting / Martin J. Osborne -- 7. Voting with asymmetric information / Martin J. Osborne -- 8. Electoral competition: two office-motivated candidates / Martin J. Osborne -- 9. Electoral competition: two policy-motivated candidates / Martin J. Osborne -- 10. Electoral competition: endogenous candidates / Martin J. Osborne -- 11. Distributive politics / Martin J. Osborne -- 12. Money in electoral competition / Martin J. Osborne -- 13. Two-period electoral competition with imperfect information / Martin J. Osborne -- 14. Bargaining / Martin J. Osborne -- 15. Regime change / Martin J. Osborne -- 16. Preferences, profiles, games, and optimization / Martin J. Osborne.  a"This volume explores topics that lie at the core of political economy: collective choice, voting, elections, bargaining, and rebellion. It presents the main formal models used to study the behavior of individuals and groups in political contexts, from choosing public policies and participating as voters and candidates in elections, to staging revolutions. Complete mathematical proofs are provided, to clarify the assumptions and deepen understanding. Part I presents models of collective choice. The main question is whether methods exist for selecting a reasonable compromise when individuals' preferences differ. Models of voting are studied in Part II. Included are models in which the individuals differ in their preferences as well as ones in which they differ in their information. One chapter considers the implications of individuals having ethical concerns, and another studies a model of sequential voting. Models of electoral competition, under the assumption of various motivations for the candidates, are discussed in Part III. One chapter is devoted to the application of these models to the study of redistributive policy. The book concludes with Part IV, which covers models of bargaining and rebellion. The book offers a rigorous yet accessible foundation for understanding how formal tools can illuminate political phenomena."--Publisher's website. 0aEconomicsxPolitical aspects. 0aVotingxMathematical models. 0aElectionsxMathematical models.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher.40uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0490zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0490.jpgzConnect to cover image04336nam a2200565 i 99101747237240896620251003151729.0m     o  d        cr##n#########251003t20252025enk     sb    000 0 eng d  z9781805116035 (hbk.)  z9781805116028 (pbk.)  a9781805116042q(pdf)  z2754-0634 (Print)  z2754-0642 (Online)  a(OCoLC)1537021937  aStSaULbengerda1 aenghlat0 aSimon,cof Faversham,d-1306,eauthor.10aQuestions on the posterior analytics (second redaction)h[electronic resource] /cSimon of Faversham ; critical edition by Iacopo Costa, Gustavo Fernández Walker, John Longeway, and Ana María Mora-Márquez ; English translation by John Longeway and Matthew Wennemann. 1aCambridge :bOpen Book Publishers,c[2025] 4c©2025  a1 online resource (xxii, 309 pages)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier1 aThe medieval text consortium seriesx2754-0642 ;vvol. 2.  aAvailable through Open Book Publishers.  aOpen access resource providing free access.  aMode of access: World Wide Web.  aThis work is licensed under an Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International (CC BY-NC 4.0) license. For more detailed information consult the publisher's website.  aAdditional resources available from the publisher's website: Faversham, Questions on the Posterior Analytics (Second Redaction), Plain Text (Latin).  aIncludes bibliography (pages 303-306).  aText in Latin with English translation ; preliminary and editorial matter in English.0 aIntroduction / Iacopo Costa, Gustavo Fernández Walker, John Longeway, Ana María Mora-Márquez -- Book 1 / Iacopo Costa, Gustavo Fernández Walker, Ana María Mora-Márquez, John Longeway, Matthew Wennemann -- Book 2 / Iacopo Costa, Ana María Mora-Márquez, Gustavo Fernández Walker, John Longeway, Matthew Wennemann -- Bibliography / Iacopo Costa, John Longeway, Ana María Mora-Márquez, Gustavo Fernández Walker.  a"Simon of Faversham was an English scholar affiliated with the University of Paris during the 1280s, where he most likely wrote his commentaries on Aristotle's philosophical works. The Posterior Analytics, one of Aristotle's most important treatises, addresses the nature of scientific demonstration. Faversham's two extant commentaries on The Posterior Analytics are invaluable witnesses to key elements of late medieval accounts of scientific demonstration, including views on the extent and limits of demonstration, its metaphysical underpinnings, and its epistemic power. The commentary edited here, together with the accompanying translation, offers new insight into Simon of Faversham's philosophy-a fascinating chapter in the history of late medieval thought. It also deepens our understanding of the philosophical discussions on demonstration and related topics that took place during the early period of Europe's university history, and of the ways in which these discussions drew on earlier philosophical developments in non-European traditions, notably the Islamic philosophical tradition.."--Publisher's website.00aAristotle.tPosterior analytics.00aSimon,cof Faversham,d-1306.tQuestiones super librum Posteriorum.00aSimon,cof Faversham,d-1306.tQuestiones super librum PosteriorumvTranslations into English. 0aDemonstration (Logic)vEarly works to 1800.1 aCosta, Iacopo,eeditor.1 aFernández Walker, Gustavo, $d 1979-eeditor.1 aAna María Mora-Márquez,eeditor.1 aLongeway, John,eeditor,etranslator.1 aWennemann, Matthew,etranslator.02aSimon,cof Faversham,d-1306.tQuestiones super librum Posteriorum.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher. 0aMedieval text consortium series ;vv. 2.x2754-064240uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0468zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0468.jpgzConnect to cover image03043nam a2200373 i 99101747357270896620251006160616.0m     o  d        cr##n#########251006t20252025enk     sb    000 0 eng d  z9781805117155 (hbk.)  z9781805117148 (pbk.)  a9781805117162q(pdf)  a(OCoLC)1540662569  aStSaULbengerda1 aGrabowski, J.q(Jan),eauthor.10aRepresentation theory :ba categorical approachh[electronic resource] /cJan E. Grabowski. 1aCambridge :bOpen Book Publishers,c[2025] 4c©2025  a1 online resource (viii, 225 pages)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aAvailable through Open Book Publishers.  aOpen access resource providing free access.  aMode of access: World Wide Web.  aThis work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International (CC BY-NC 4.0) license. For more detailed information consult the publisher's website.  aIncludes bibliography (pages 211-213) and indexes.0 aIntroduction / Jan E. Grabowski -- 1. Algebra / Jan E. Grabowski -- 2. Categories / Jan E. Grabowski -- 3. Representations / Jan E. Grabowski -- 4. Modules /   Jan E. Grabowski -- 5. Examples / Jan E. Grabowski -- 6. Advanced topics / Jan E. Grabowski.  a"This volume offers a fresh and modern introduction to one of abstract algebra's key topics. Guiding readers through the transition between structure theory and representation theory, this textbook explores how algebraic objects like groups and rings act as symmetries of other structures. Using the accessible yet powerful language of category theory, the book reimagines standard approaches to topics such as modules and algebras in a way that unlocks modern treatments of more advanced topics such as quiver representations and even representations of Hopf algebras and categories. Aimed at undergraduate students with prior exposure to linear algebra and basic group theory, the book introduces categories early and uses them throughout, providing a cohesive framework that mirrors current mathematical research. Though technically sophisticated, it also includes examples and exercises designed to develop intuition and understanding. Grabowski's inclusion of computational tools such as SageMath offers a valuable and traditionally underdeveloped bridge between abstract theory and hands-on exploration. This is a uniquely valuable guide for students ready to stretch their understanding of the subject's conceptual depth and evolving frontiers."--Publisher's website. 0aRepresentations of algebras.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher.40uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0492zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0492.jpgzConnect to cover image03650nam a2200505 i 99101747899250896620251117145532.0m     o  d        cr||n|||||||||251010t20252025enkad   sb    001 0 eng d  z9781805113355 (hbk.)  z9781805113348 (pbk.)  a9781805113362q(pdf)  z2632-6906 (Print)  z2632-6914 (Online)  a(OCoLC)1544803083  aStSaULbengerda  aa-jo---1 aHerin, Bruno,eauthor.12aA grammar of Jordanian Arabich[electronic resource] :cBruno Herin and Enam Al-Wer. 1aCambridge :bOpen Book Publishers,c[2025] 4c©2025  a1 online resource (xxvi, 499 pages) :b12 illustrations, 230 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier1 aCambridge Semitic languages and culturesx2632-6914 ;vvol. 39  aAvailable through Open Book Publishers.  aOpen access resource providing free access.  aMode of access: World Wide Web.  aThis work is licensed under an Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International (CC BY-NC 4.0) license. For more detailed information consult the publisher's website.  aAt head of front cover: Cambridge Semitic languages and cultures.  aAt foot of cover: University of Cambridge, Faculty of Asian and Middle Eastern Studies.  aIncludes bibliography (pages 475-490) and indexes.  aChiefly English ; text examples in Latin, Hebrew, Greek and Aramaic.0 a1. Introduction / Bruno Herin, Enam Al-Wer -- 2. Phonology / Bruno Herin, Enam Al-Wer -- 3. Morphology / Enam Al-Wer, Bruno Herin -- 4. Syntax / Bruno Herin, Enam Al-Wer -- 5. Texts / Bruno Herin, Enam Al-Wer.  a"The present grammar is based on empirical data collected over more than three decades. It investigates the phonology and morphosyntax of Jordanian Arabic, with a focus on the traditional sedentary varieties of Central and Northern Jordan, locally known as Balgawi and Horani. Although theory-neutral, the description is typologically informed and should be accessible to anyone broadly acquainted with linguistics. The structure of the grammar follows the traditional division between phonology, morphology and syntax. The phonology chapter discusses both segmental and suprasegmental features. The morphology section investigates the structure of the major word classes, both open and closed, as well as minor classes such as interjections, discourse markers and other uninflected particles. The chapter on syntax explores the internal structure of noun and verb phrases and the syntax of simple and complex clauses as well as transversal phenomena such as agreement, negation and information structure. The book also includes a section devoted to the social dialectology of Jordan, and a discussion of the data upon which the grammar is based and three transcribed and translated texts belonging to the traditional dialect."--Publisher's website. 0aArabic languagexGrammar. 0aArabic languagezJordan.1 aAl-Wer, Enam,eauthor.2 aUniversity of Cambridge.bFaculty of Asian and Middle Eastern Studies.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher. 0aSemitic languages and cultures ;vv. 39.x2632-691440uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0410zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0410.jpgzConnect to cover image03727nam a2200445 i 99101747899260896620251010163310.0m     o  d        cr##n#########251011t20252025enka    sb    000 0 eng d  z9781805116974 (hbk.)  z9781805116967 (pbk.)  a9781805117001q(HTML)  a9781805116998q(EPUB)  a9781805116981q(PDF)  a(OCoLC)1540663962  aStSaULbengerda1 aMcMorran, Will,eauthor.10aSensing violence :breading with the Marquis de Sadeh[electronic resource] /cWill McMorran. 1aCambridge :bOpen Book Publishers,c[2025] 4c©2025  a1 online resource (xiv, 252 pages) :b6 illustrations.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aAvailable through Open Book Publishers.  aOpen access resource providing free access.  aMode of access: World Wide Web.  aThis work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International (CC BY-NC 4.0) license. For more detailed information consult the publisher's website.  aEPUB Accessibility Report available from publisher's website.  aAdditional resources available from publisher's website: Eugénie Questionnaire and Justine Questionnaire.  aIncludes bibliography (pages 221-241) and index.0 aIntroduction / Will McMorran - 1. Looking and touching with Eugénie / Will McMorran - 2. Hearing and feeling with Justine / Will McMorran - 3. Translating with Sade / Will McMorran - 4. Teaching with Sade / Will McMorran - Conclusion / Will McMorran.  a"What does reading fictional violence do to us as readers? To find out, this provocative and original book turns to the works of an author synonymous with sexual violence: the Marquis de Sade. Drawing on psychology, cognitive literary studies, and empirical research, it argues that reading is a fundamentally embodied act - and one that implicates us far more than we might like to think in fictional depictions of violence. This book turns not just to Sade for answers, but to his readers. Where previous studies have focussed either on Sade's language or his philosophy, this one places the lived experience of actual readers at the heart of its investigations. Taking particular scenes from Sade's fiction, from a young girl posing as a statue in 'Eugénie de Franval' to the brutal rape of the heroine of Justine, this book explores what happens not just on the page but in the minds and bodies of readers as they bring these scenes to life. Drawing on questionnaires completed by readers of those scenes, and on his own experience as a reader, teacher and translator of Sade, the author challenges the disembodied approach that has dominated Sade studies and literary criticism more broadly over recent decades. This is not just a book about Sade-it's a radical exploration of what happens to us when we are confronted with scenes of violence. Urgent, accessible, and personal, it offers a new model for understanding reading as a matter of making sensations as well as making sense."--Publisher's website.10aSade,cmarquis de,d1740-1814xCriticism and interpretation. 0aViolence in literaturexPsychological aspects. 0aRape in literaturexPsychological aspects.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher.40uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0488zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0488.jpgzConnect to cover image05056nam a2200457 i 99101748303550896620251117151158.0m     o  d        cr||n|||||||||251028t20252025enka    sb    001 0 eng d  z9781805116080 (hbk.)  z9781805116073 (pbk.)  a9781805116097q(pdf)  a9781805116110q(HTML)  a9781805116103q(EPUB)  a(OCoLC)1547601119  aStSaULbengerda00aPerformance research methods :binterdisciplinary methods for theatre, dance and performance studiesh[electronic resource] /cedited by Liesbeth Groot Nibbelink and Laura Karreman. 1aCambridge :bOpen Book Publishers,c[2025] 4c©2025  a1 online resource (xxii, 456 pages) :b18 colour illustrations.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2r