e broader social fabric. By introducing chimeracords-hybrid sound objects forged from factory detritus-and their affordance for sonic experimentation, 'Hylo Narrans' challenges Western narratives of purity, utility, and control, inviting readers to consider alternative storylines posed by materials-in-flight. Weaving theories of marronage through situated acoustic knowledge, this book is essential reading for those working at the intersection of sound, matter, and community. It speaks to experimental musicians, sound artists, artistic researchers, and theorists interested in how sonic materiality relates to social space, cultural memory, and communal wellbeing. With a deep commitment to sonic collectivity and intermaterial dialogue, this volume reimagines the workshop as a site of resistance, resonance, and relational creativity."--Publisher's website. 0aBrass instrumentsxAcoustics. 0aMetalsxAcoustic properties. 0aMaroonsxSocial life and customs. 0aMusicxSocial aspects.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher.40uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0476zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0476.jpgzConnect to cover image03988nam a2200505 i 99101748303830896620251117125052.0m     o  d        cr||n|||||||||251023t20252025enkad   sb    001 0 eng d  z9781805115984 (hbk.)  z9781805115977 (pbk.)  a9781805115991q(pdf)  a9781805116011q(HTML)  a9781805116004q(EPUB)  z0265-0649 (Print)  z2977-845X (Online)  a(OCoLC)1546825822  aStSaULbengerda1 aEzenwafor-Afuecheta, Chikelu I.,eauthor.10aGrammar of Etulo :ba Niger-Congo (Idomoid) languageh[electronic resource] :cChikelu I. Ezenwafor-Afuecheta. 1aCambridge :bOpen Book Publishers,c[2025] 4c©2025  a1 online resource (xxiv, 272 pages) :b5 illustrations, 28 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier1 aPublications of the Philological Societyx2977-845X ;vvol. 1  aAvailable through Open Book Publishers.  aOpen access resource providing free access.  aMode of access: World Wide Web.  aThis work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International (CC BY-NC 4.0) license. For more detailed information consult the publisher's website.  aAt head of front cover: Publications of the Philological Society.  aEPUB Accessibility Report available from the publisher's website.  aLinks to audio recordings are available from the publisher's website.  aIncludes bibliography (pages 258-264) and index.0 a1. General Introduction / Chikelu I. Ezenwafor-Afuecheta -- 2. The Phonology of Etulo / Chikelu I. Ezenwafor-Afuecheta -- 3. Morphological Processes / Chikelu I. Ezenwafor-Afuecheta -- 4. Word Classes / Chikelu I. Ezenwafor-Afuecheta -- 5. Aspects of Etulo Syntax / Chikelu I. Ezenwafor-Afuecheta -- 6. Valency, Transitivity and Serialization / Chikelu I. Ezenwafor-Afuecheta -- 7. Tense, Aspect and Modality / Chikelu I. Ezenwafor-Afuecheta -- 8. General Conclusion / Chikelu I. Ezenwafor-Afuecheta.  a"This work provides the first detailed linguistic description of the grammar of Etulo, a language spoken in Nigeria by a minority group in Benue and Taraba states. This description establishes Etulo as a tone language characterised by a predominant SVO word order, non-inflectional morphology, prominent aspectual values, obligatory complement verbs and verb serialization, among other features. This grammar also serves as a foundation for further description of the Etulo grammar and for the development of pedagogical materials needed in Etulo language teaching. Within the Benue-Congo sub group of languages, Etulo is classified as an Idomoid language alongside seven other languages with which it shares striking linguistic similarities. These include Idoma, Igede, Yatye, Alago, Akweya, Akpa, and Eloyi, none of which has yet received a robust linguistic description in the form of a grammar. This work therefore serves as a reference work not only for Etulo, but also for other Idomoid languages yet to be described. This volume will be of interest to researchers of African linguistics in general and Idomoid languages in particular, as well as Africanists, comparative linguists and language typologists more generally."--Publisher's website. 0aEtulo (African people) 0aBenue-Congo languages.2 aPhilological Society (Great Britain),eissuing body,efunder.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher. 0aPublications of the Philological Society ;vv. 1.x2977-845X40uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0467zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0467.jpgzConnect to cover image05838nam a2200517 i 99101748352960896620251117125432.0m        d        cr##n#########251031t20252025enk     sb    000 0 eng d  z9781805117186 (Hardback)  z9781805117179 (Paperback)  a9781805117193q(pdf)  a9781805117216q(HTML)  a9781805117209q(epub)  z2054-216X (Print)  a2054-2178 (Online)  a(OCoLC)1547601092  aStSaULbengerda1 aenghgre1 aPitsipios, Iakōvos G.,d1802-1865 or 9,eauthor.10aPithekos Xouth.lEnglish.f202510aXouth, the ape :ba tale of mannersh[electronic resource] /cIakovos Pitsipios ; translated by Neo G. Christodoulides. 1aCambridge :bOpen Book Publishers,c2025. 4c©2025  a1 online resource (x, 92 pages)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier1 aOpen Book classics seriesx2054-2178 ;vvol. 13  aAvailable through Open Book Publishers.  aOpen access resource providing free access.  aMode of access: World Wide Web.  aThe text of this work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International license (CC BY 4.0). For more detailed information consult the publisher's website.  aEPUB Accessibility Report available from the publisher's website.  aIncludes bibliography (pages 87-88).  aText translated from the Modern Greek into English ; foreword and introduction in English.0 aIntroduction: The Literary Precursors of Xouth, the Ape / Iakovos Pitsipios, Neo Gereon Christodoulides -- 1. Kallistratos Evgenides and Xouth, the Ape / Iakovos Pitsipios, Neo Gereon Christodoulides -- 2. The Journey / Iakovos Pitsipios, Neo Gereon Christodoulides -- 3. The Recognition / Iakovos Pitsipios, Neo Gereon Christodoulides -- 4. The Release / Iakovos Pitsipios, Neo Gereon Christodoulides -- 5. The Crime / Iakovos Pitsipios, Neo Gereon Christodoulides -- 6. Divine Justice / Iakovos Pitsipios, Neo Gereon Christodoulides -- 7. The Wilderness / Iakovos Pitsipios, Neo Gereon Christodoulides -- 8. The Captivity / Iakovos Pitsipios, Neo Gereon Christodoulides -- 9. Ligarides / Iakovos Pitsipios, Neo Gereon Christodoulides -- 10. The Return / Iakovos Pitsipios, Neo Gereon Christodoulides -- 11. The Sweet Little Soultana / Iakovos Pitsipios, Neo Gereon Christodoulides -- 12. The True Love of Fashionable Women, or the Yellow Ball Gown / Iakovos Pitsipios, Neo Gereon Christodoulides -- 13. The Journey of Xouth with Maloukatos and Ligarides / Iakovos Pitsipios, Neo Gereon Christodoulides -- 14. The Four Great Trials of My 'Sister' in Three Hours / Iakovos Pitsipios, Neo Gereon Christodoulides -- 15. Master Ligarides Is Writing His Fashionable Travelogue / Iakovos Pitsipios, Neo Gereon Christodoulides - 16. Maloukatos' Thoughts on the Travelogue of Master Ligarides / Iakovos Pitsipios, Neo Gereon Christodoulides -- 17. The Malady / Iakovos Pitsipios, Neo Gereon Christodoulides.  a"'Xouth, the Ape', published in 1848 by Iakovos Pitsipios is a pioneering and satirical Greek novel that deftly blends humour, cultural critique, and biting social commentary. The novel is set in the aftermath of the Greek War of Independence. The story follows a young Greek man, desperate to present himself as a European aristocrat, who finds himself entangled with Xouth-an ape who is, in fact, a German travel writer transformed as punishment for his vanity and prejudices. Through the interactions between the protagonist and the ape-valet, Pitsipios skewers the pretensions of Greece's newly minted elites, exposing the often comical efforts to mimic Western manners and ideals. The novel lampoons the wave of Western travel writers who 'discovered' Greece, poking fun at their colonial attitudes and superficial observations. The figure of Xouth serves as both a mirror and a caricature, reflecting the absurdities of identity, authenticity, and cultural imitation in a society striving to define itself between East and West. Translated in English for the first time, with an expansive Introduction by Neo G. Christodoulides, the novel explores themes of national identity, the pitfalls of mimicry, and the complexities of cultural exchange. Rich with allusions to both Greek and European literary traditions, Pitsipios draws sharp parallels between his characters' quests for legitimacy and the real historical debates around language, class, and belonging in 19th-century Greece. The novel's polyglossic style-a blend of archaic, official, and colloquial Greek-further emphasises the layered and fractured nature of Greek identity at the time. Despite its initial obscurity, the novel's relevance endures: its sharp satire and insightful social analysis make it not just a humorous adventure, but a revealing document of post-revolutionary Greece and its ongoing negotiations with modernity, Western influence, and self-perception. 'Xouth, the Ape' is a hidden gem that deserves renewed attention from readers, scholars, and anyone fascinated by the crossroads of cultures."--Publisher's website.10aHölderlin, Friedrich,d1770-1843xCriticism and interpretation.10aHölderlin, Friedrich,d1770-1843.tHyperion.1 aChristodoulides, Neo G.,etranslator.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher. 0aOpen Book classics ;vv. 13.x2054-217840uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0493zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0493.jpg