Europe, Hartlib spent his adult life in London, where he became a prolific correspondent and chronicler. His Ephemerides, spanning 1634 to 1660, and his extensive correspondence with leading thinkers across Britain and Protestant Europe offer an unparalleled window into the era's religious, political, and scientific ferment. This volume goes beyond previous studies in both scope and depth, drawing extensively on archival sources and offering new interpretations of Hartlib's network and influence. Organized chronologically, it explores the wide-ranging social, economic, and ideological pursuits of Hartlib and his collaborators-many of them renowned figures in their own right-and his close alignment with the Cromwellian cause. Providing the most complete portrait to date of the Hartlib circle's emergence and impact, this study sets a new benchmark for scholarship and invites renewed engagement with one of the early modern period's most visionary projects of knowledge, reform, and communication."--Publisher's website.10aHartlib, Samuel,d-1662. 0aEuropexHistoryxReligious aspectsvSources. 0aEuropexHistoryy17th centuryvSources.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher.40uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0486zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0486.jpgzConnect to cover image04453nam a2200529 i 99101749507890896620251111142124.0m     o  d        cr##n#########251111t20252025enk     sb    001 0 eng d  z9781805117414 (hbk.)  z9781805117407 (pbk.)  a9781805117421q(pdf)  z2632-6906 (Print)  z2632-6914 (Online)  aStSaULbengerda04aThe intertwined world of the oral and written transmission of sacred traditions in the Middle Easth[electronic resource]  /cedited by Alba Fedeli, Geoffrey Khan and Johan Lundberg. 1aCambridge :bOpen Book Publishers,c[2025] 4c©2025  a1 online resource (xiv, 470 pages)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier1 aCambridge S