view with Nevine El Souefi(pp. 273-290)    Linda Herrera17. National Geographic Learning Joins Education 2.0: Interview with Tom Kelley(pp. 291-310)    Nariman MoustafaLinda Herrera18. Motivations for the Digital Transformation of Education: Interview with Ahmed Daher(pp. 311-326)    Linda HerreraHany Zayed19. Coordinating the State's Knowledge Project: Interview with Mahmoud Dawoud and Mahmoud Hussein(pp. 327-340)    Linda Herrera20. The Dream of Developing a Knowledge Bank for All: Interview with Majed M. Al Sadek(pp. 341-360)    Linda Herrera21. Building the Knowledge Bank from Scratch: Interview with Mohamed El-Araby(pp. 361-372)    Linda Herrera22. Making Education Entertaining: Interview with Mai Magdy(pp. 373-390)    Linda Herrera23. Digital Transformation and the Changing EdTech Landscape in Egypt(pp. 391-414)    Hany Zayed24. The Learning Journey of a High School Student from the Historic Class of 2021(pp. 417-436)    Linda HerreraNairy AbdElShafy25. The Rise, Fall, and Aftermath of Take-Home Research Projects(pp. 437-456)    Linda HerreraHeba Shama26. 'Survival of the Fittest': A High School Student's Perspective on Learning, Ethics, and Why Students Cheat(pp. 457-474)    Linda Herrera27. Teachers in Search of Their Identity: A View from Ismailia during Times of Change(pp. 475-492)    Mohamed ElsayedMenna Ahmed28. Primary School Teachers Leverage Social Media for Professional Development(pp. 493-508)    Menna AhmedAyman AlhusseiniLinda Herrera29. A New Curriculum and a Pandemic: Primary Teachers' Strategies(pp. 509-522)    Nevine El Souefi  a"Education 2.0 offers a compelling portrait of Egypt's bold attempt to overhaul its public education system amid sweeping political and technological transformation. Drawing on extensive oral history interviews, this book traces the launch and rollout of the 'New Education System' initiated by the Ministry of Education in 2018, designed to modernize curriculum, pedagogy, and assessment in the digital age and change the 'culture of learning'. The volume moves fluidly from macro-level state planning to the lived experiences of teachers and students, exploring the promises and pitfalls of top-down reform. Conducted partly during the COVID-19 pandemic, the research captures Egypt's first large-scale experiment with hybrid and distance learning. Interviews with key actors-from policymakers and tech developers to students and educators-reveal competing visions, unintended consequences, and the challenges of culturally transforming education systems in a middle-income country where private tutoring is rife, the sector is chronically under resourced, and politics overshadows policy. This book is essential reading for scholars, practitioners, and policymakers interested in education reform, digital transformation, and the role of the state in shaping learning futures in the Global South. It is also an excellent case study for courses in Middle East studies and comparative and international education."--Publisher's website. 0aEducationxEffect of technological innovations onzEgypt.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher.40uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0489zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0489.jpgzConnect to cover image03898nam a2200421 u 99101750548190896620251205125045.0a     sb    00100 cr#|n|nnn|||||251205t20252025enk     sb    001 0 eng d  z9781805117100 (Hardback)  z9781805117094 (Paperback)  a9781805117117q(PDF)  a9781805117131q(HTML)  a9781805117124q(EPUB)  aStSaULbengerda00aSolidarity in contingency :bRorty's constructive projecth[electronic resource] /cedited by Elin Danielsen Huckerby and Marianne Janack. 1aCambridge :bOpen Book Publishers,c2025. 4c©2025  a1 online resource (xii, 230 pages)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomupterbc2rdamedia  avolumebcr2rdacarrier  aAvailable through Open Book Publishers.  aOpen access resource providing free access.  aMode of access: World Wide Web.  aThis work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International license (CC BY-NC 4.0). For more detailed information consult the publisher's website.  aEPUB Accessibility Report available from the publisher's website.  aIncludes bibliography (pages 201-219) and index.0 a1. Introduction: From Explication to Application / Elin D. Huckerby, Marianne Janack -- 2. Rorty's Interpretations and the Possibility of Social Change / Marianne Janack -- 3. Tenderness as the Norm: Rorty on 'Intense Mental Pain' / Paul Giladi -- 4. Actually (Anti-)Utopian? Levitas, Rorty and the Conditions of Utopianism / Elin D. Huckerby -- 5. Pragmatist Eirenism in Post-Truth Society / Michela Bella -- 6. Creative Doubts against Authoritarian Certainty: Rorty through Reparative Critique / Heidi Salaverría -- 7. Rortyan Irony as Civic Virtue in Our Myside Society / Martin Müller -- 8. Irony as Hope and the Future of the Humanities / Bryan Vescio.  a"Richard Rorty (1931-2007), once dubbed 'the man who killed truth', is best known for challenging the idea that philosophy provides foundational knowledge. Yet beyond the controversy lies a vital, underexplored side of Rorty's work: his constructive vision for fostering democratic solidarity in a world shaped by contingency and uncertainty. This volume shifts focus from defending Rorty to applying his insights for today's fractured, post-truth culture. Centered on Rorty's "Contingency, Irony, and Solidarity" (1989), the collection explores how his pragmatism helps us reimagine philosophy as a cultural practice-one grounded not in timeless truths, but in shared hopes, vocabularies, and democratic cooperation. The volume brings together seven original essays that revisit Rortyan concepts like liberal ironism, poetic redescription, eirenism, and democratic solidarity, and explore their implications for social justice, feminist theory, public discourse, and the humanities. Rather than lament relativism or retreat into essentialism, these contributions demonstrate how Rorty's philosophy offers practical, imaginative tools for navigating difference and building inclusive societies. Emphasizing creativity over certainty and solidarity over skepticism, this timely volume reclaims Rorty's legacy as a philosopher of hope-and a resource for democratic renewal in our era of radical uncertainty."--Publisher's website.10aRorty, RichardxContributions to philosophy.10aRorty, Richard.tContingency, irony, and solidarity.1 aHuckerby, Elin D.,eeditor.1 aJanack, Marianne,eeditor.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher.40uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0487zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0487.jpgzConnect to cover image05440nam a2200529 u 99101751106060896620251212103805.0aad   sb    000 0 cr#|n||||||||n251211t20252025enkad   sb    000 0 eng d  z9781805117445 (Hardback)  z9781805117438 (Paperback)  a9781805117452q(PDF)  a9781805117476q(HTML)  a9781805117469q(EPUB)  z2399-6668 (Print)  a2399-6676 (Online)  aStSaULbengerda  ae------00aMore with more :binvesting in the energy transition : 2025 European Public Investment Outlookh[electronic resource] /cedited by Floriana Cerniglia and Francesco Saraceno. 1aCambridge :bOpen Book Publishers,c2025. 4c©2025  a1 online resource (xvi, 256 pages) :b43 illustrations, 11 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier1 aOpen reports seriesx2399-6676 ;vvol. 14  aAvailable through Open Book Publishers.  aOpen access resource providing free access.  aMode of access: World Wide Web.  aThis work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International license (CC BY-NC 4.0). For more detailed information consult the publisher's website.  aAdditional resources available from the publisher's website.  aEPUB Accessibility Report available from the publisher's website.  aIncludes bibliographical references.0 aPreface -- Introduction: Energy Transition in the EU-The Need for a Governance Revolution / Floriana Cerniglia, Francesco Saraceno -- 1. An EU-wide Perspective on Public Investment in the Energy Transition / Andrea Brasili, Bertrand Magné, Ege Öndeş, Debora Revoltella, Annamaria Tueske -- 2. France: Preserving Investment in the Energy Transition in an Unstable Policy Environment /Paul Malliet, Mathieu Plane, Francesco Saraceno, Anissa Saumtally -- 3. The Role of Public Support for the Energy Transition in Germany: Past and Future Tasks / Tom Bauermann -- 4. Energy Transition and Public Investment in Italy / Giovanni Barbieri, Floriana Cerniglia, Andrea Pronti -- 5. Investment in the Energy Transition in Spain / Ignacio Alvarez, Jorge Uxó -- 6. Tackling the Drawbacks of Past and Current EU Energy Transition Policies: The Need for a Cooperative, Mission-oriented Industrial Strategy / Francesco Gracceva, Daniela Palma -- 7. Energy Transition and Industrial Competitiveness in the EU / Mirko Armiento, Andrea Villa -- 8. Research and Innovation Policy for the Energy Transition in the EU / Francesco Pasimeni, Willem Klok, Floor Alkemade -- 9. On Grids: The Backbone of the Energy Transition / Antonella Battaglini, Katharina Sikow-Magny -- 10. Investing in Critical Raw Materials for the Clean-Tech Transition in the EU / Roberto Zoboli -- 11. The EU Strategy for Green Hydrogen: More with Less (Public Investment)? / Rafael Fernández, Clara García -- 12. The Power of Energy Communities for a Just Transition in Europe / Francesc Cots, Jérémie Fosse, Diana Mangalagiu -- 13. Making the ETS2 Socially Acceptable through Carbon Revenue Redistribution and Investments / Andreas Eisl, Phuc-Vinh Nguyen -- 14. (How) Can the Energy Transition in Europe be a Just Transition? / Bela Galgóczi, Andrew Watt.  a"This outlook offers a timely and insightful exploration of Europe's energy transition, a process that lies at the heart of today's environmental, economic, and political debates. It examines the diverse commitments undertaken by European countries as they navigate the challenges of decarbonization and the shift to sustainable energy systems. By analyzing both the policy frameworks and the concrete instruments adopted to reach ambitious climate and energy goals, the book sheds light on the strategies shaping the continent's future. A particular emphasis is placed on the role of public investment, highlighting how state action can catalyze innovation, support infrastructure, and bridge gaps where market forces alone may fall short. Through this lens, the volume not only evaluates existing practices but also considers the broader implications for governance, equity, and long-term resilience. Written with clarity and rigor, the outlook will be of interest to policymakers, scholars, and practitioners seeking to understand the dynamics of Europe's green transition. It invites readers to consider the balance between national priorities and collective European objectives, offering valuable insights into how commitments translate into action-and how public investment can be a decisive lever for change."--Publisher's website. 0aClean energyxEconomic aspectszEurope. 0aEnergy transitionzEurope. 0aSustainable developmentzEurope.  aClean energy investmentzEurope. 0aPublic investmentszEurope.1 aCerniglia, Floriana,eeditor.1 aSaraceno, Francesco,eeditor.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher. 0aOpen reports series ;vv. 14.x2399-667640uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0499zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0499.jbgzConnect to cover image04192nam a2200517 u 99101751116010896620251218093118.0aa    sb    001 0dcr#|n||||||||n251212t20252025enka    sb    001 0deng d  z9781805117490 (Hardback)  z9781805117483 (Paperback)  a9781805117506q(PDF)  a9781805117520q(HTML)  a9781805117513q(EPUB)  aStSaULbengerda1 aLisboa, Maria Manuel,d1963-eauthor.10aBroken :billness and disability in Antônio Francisco Lisboa, Camilo Castelo Branco, Clarice Lispector, Victor Willing, Paula Rego and Ana Palmah[electronic resource] /cMaria Manuel Lisboa. 1aCambridge :bOpen Book Publishers,c2025. 4c©2025  a1 online resource (xxiv, 206 pages) :b73 colour illustrations.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  aunmediatedbn2rdamedia  avolumebnc2rdacarrier  aAvailable through Open Book Publishers.  aOpen access resource providing free access.  aMode of access: World Wide Web.  aThis work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International license (CC BY-NC 4.0). For more detailed information consult the publisher's website.  aEPUB Accessibility Report available from the publisher's website.  aIncludes bibliographies at the end of each chapter, bibliographical references and index.0 aIntroduction: Faulty Merchandise / Maria Manuel Lisboa -- 1. Little Cripples: Antônio Francisco Lisboa ('O Aleijadinho') / Maria Manuel Lisboa -- 2. Camilo Castelo Branco's A brasileira de Prazins: 'When in Danger or in Doubt, Run in Circles, Scream and Shout'(pp. 31-56)    Maria Manuel Lisboa3. 'I Know Where You Were Last Night': Clarice Lispector or When Stars Become Supernovas(pp. 57-84)    Maria Manuel Lisboa4. Victor Willing: Being There(pp. 85-118)    Maria Manuel Lisboa5. Paula Rego: A Brick through a Window Never Comes with a Love Note / Maria Manuel Lisboa -- 6. Menstrous/Monstrous: Bleeding, Amenorrhea and Feminine Hygiene in the Art of Ana Palma and Paula Rego / Maria Manuel Lisboa -- Interview with Lila Nunes / Maria Manuel Lisboa -- Interview with Ana Palma / Maria Manuel Lisboa -- In memoriam: Paula Rego and the Stories Left Untold / Maria Manuel Lisboa.  a"'Broken: Illness and Disability in Antônio Francisco Lisboa, Camilo Castelo Branco, Clarice Lispector, Victor Willing, Paula Rego and Ana Palma' traces the lives and works of six major artists and writers from Portugal, Brazil, and Britain through the lens of 'being broken'-in body, mind, or both. Spanning from the eighteenth century to the present, the volume explores how sociopolitical and somatic factors such as mental illness, psychological abuse, arthritis, genital mutilation, and multiple sclerosis shaped their creativity, while also reflecting broader national, social, sexual, and political  pressures.Engaging both literature and visual art, the book offers an original and provocative perspective that unsettles conventional narratives of health, gender, and identity in Lusophone and transnational contexts. By situating canonical figures alongside emerging voices, 'Broken' bridges generations and disciplines, revealing how art and fiction transform experiences of illness and disability into critical insights on society, history, and power."--Publisher's website.10aLisboa, Antônio Francisco,d1730?-1814.10aCastelo Branco, Camilo,d1825-1890.10aLispector, Clarice.10aWilling, Victor,d1928-1988.10aRego, Paula.10aPalma, Ana. 0aDisability studies. 0aArtists with disabilities. 0aAuthors with disabilities. 0aArtistsxMental health. 0aAuthorsxMental health.2 aOpen Book Publishers,epublisher.40uhttps://doi.org/10.11647/OBP.0500zConnect to e-book42uhttps://cdn.openbookpublishers.com/covers/10.11647/obp.0500.jpgzConnect to cover image